    {
      "content": "Create and Use a Shared Access Signature",
      "pos": [
        7155,
        7195
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A shared access signature (SAS) is a URI that grants restricted access rights to a storage resource for a specified time interval.",
      "pos": [
        7196,
        7326
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can create a SAS on these storage resources:",
      "pos": [
        7327,
        7375
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Containers and blobs",
      "pos": [
        7379,
        7399
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Queues",
      "pos": [
        7402,
        7408
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Tables",
      "pos": [
        7411,
        7417
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "File shares and files",
      "pos": [
        7420,
        7441
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By providing a client with a shared access signature, you can enable them to access resources in your storage account without sharing your account key with them.",
      "pos": [
        7444,
        7605
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        7608,
        7780
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> For an in-depth conceptual overview and tutorial on shared access signatures, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Shared Access Signatures<ept id=\"p1\">](storage-dotnet-shared-access-signature-part-1.md)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "The shared access signature URI query parameters incorporate all of the information necessary to grant controlled access to a storage resource.",
      "pos": [
        7782,
        7925
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The URI query parameters on a SAS include the time interval over which the shared access signature is valid, the permissions that it grants, the resource that is to be made available, the version to use to execute the request, and the signature that the storage services will use to authenticate the request.",
      "pos": [
        7926,
        8234
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Additionally, the shared access signature URI can reference a stored access policy that provides an additional level of control over a set of signatures, including the ability to modify or revoke access to the resource if necessary.",
      "pos": [
        8236,
        8468
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8471,
        8640
      ],
      "content": "For information on the URI format of a shared access signature, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Delegating Access with a Shared Access Signature<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/ee395415.aspx)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Secure use of Shared Access Signatures",
      "pos": [
        8646,
        8684
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A shared access signature grants access to the resource specified by the URI's granted permissions.",
      "pos": [
        8685,
        8784
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should always use HTTPS to construct a shared access signature URI.",
      "pos": [
        8785,
        8856
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using HTTP with shared access signatures can make your storage account vulnerable to malicious use.",
      "pos": [
        8857,
        8956
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If a shared access signature grants access that is not intended for the general public, then it should be constructed with the fewest possible permissions.",
      "pos": [
        8958,
        9113
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, a shared access signature should be distributed securely to clients over a secure connection, should be associated with a stored access policy for the purpose of revocation, and should specify the shortest possible lifetime for the signature.",
      "pos": [
        9114,
        9369
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> A shared access signature URI is associated with the account key used to create the signature, and the associated stored access policy (if any).",
      "pos": [
        9372,
        9529
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If no stored access policy is specified, the only way to revoke a shared access signature is to change the account key.",
      "pos": [
        9530,
        9649
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Creating a Shared Access Signature",
      "pos": [
        9656,
        9690
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following code example creates an access policy on a container and then generates a shared access signature for the container.",
      "pos": [
        9691,
        9821
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This shared access signature can then be given to clients:",
      "pos": [
        9822,
        9880
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using a Shared Access Signature",
      "pos": [
        12180,
        12211
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A client who receives a shared access signature can use it from their code to construct an object of type <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>StorageCredentials<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/microsoft.windowsazure.storage.auth.storagecredentials.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12212,
        12435
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Those credentials can then be used to construct a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>CloudStorageAccount<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/microsoft.windowsazure.storage.cloudstorageaccount.aspx)</ept> or a <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>CloudBlobClient<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/microsoft.windowsazure.storage.blob.cloudblobclient.aspx)</ept> object for working with the resource, as shown in this example:",
      "pos": [
        12436,
        12779
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use a Stored Access Policy",
      "pos": [
        13436,
        13462
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A stored access policy provides an additional level of control over shared access signatures on the server side.",
      "pos": [
        13463,
        13575
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Establishing a stored access policy serves to group shared access signatures and to provide additional restrictions for signatures that are bound by the policy.",
      "pos": [
        13576,
        13736
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use a stored access policy to change the start time, expiry time, or permissions for a signature, or to revoke it after it has been issued.",
      "pos": [
        13737,
        13884
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A stored access policy gives you greater control over shared access signatures you have released.",
      "pos": [
        13886,
        13983
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Instead of specifying the signature's lifetime and permissions on the URL, you can specify these parameters on a stored access policy that is stored on the container, file share, queue, or table that contains the resource being shared.",
      "pos": [
        13984,
        14219
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To change these parameters for one or more signatures, you can modify the stored access policy, rather than reissuing the signatures.",
      "pos": [
        14220,
        14353
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also quickly revoke the signature by modifying the stored access policy.",
      "pos": [
        14354,
        14434
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, suppose you have issued a shared access signature that's associated with a stored access policy.",
      "pos": [
        14436,
        14545
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you've specified the expiry time within the stored access policy, you can modify the access policy to extend the life of the signature, without having to reissue a new signature.",
      "pos": [
        14546,
        14727
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Best practices recommend specifying a stored access policy for any signed resource for which you are issuing a shared access signature, as the stored policy can be used to modify or revoke the signature after it has been issued.",
      "pos": [
        14729,
        14957
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you don't specify a stored policy, it's recommended that you limit the lifetime of your signature in order to minimize any risk to your storage account resources.",
      "pos": [
        14958,
        15123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Associating a Shared Access Signature with a Stored Access Policy",
      "pos": [
        15130,
        15195
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A stored access policy includes a name up to 64 characters long that is unique within the container, file share, queue, or table.",
      "pos": [
        15196,
        15325
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To associate a shared access signature with a stored access policy, you specify this identifier when creating the shared access signature.",
      "pos": [
        15326,
        15464
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the shared access signature URI, the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>signedidentifier<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> field specifies the identifier for the stored access policy.",
      "pos": [
        15465,
        15584
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A container, file share, queue, or table can include up to 5 stored access policies.",
      "pos": [
        15586,
        15670
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each policy can be used by any number of shared access signatures.",
      "pos": [
        15671,
        15737
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>When you establish a stored access policy on a container, file share, queue, or table, it may take up to 30 seconds to take effect.",
      "pos": [
        15740,
        15883
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "During this interval, a shared access signature that is associated with the stored access policy will fail with status code 403 (Forbidden), until the access policy becomes active.",
      "pos": [
        15884,
        16064
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specifying Access Policy Parameters for a Shared Access Policy",
      "pos": [
        16070,
        16132
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The stored access policy can specify the following access policy parameters for the signatures with which it's associated:",
      "pos": [
        16133,
        16255
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Start time",
      "pos": [
        16259,
        16269
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Expiry time",
      "pos": [
        16273,
        16284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Permissions",
      "pos": [
        16288,
        16299
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Depending on how you want to control access to your storage resource, you can specify all of these parameters within the stored access policy, and omit them from the URL for the shared access signature.",
      "pos": [
        16301,
        16503
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Doing so permits you to modify the associated signature's behavior at any time, as well as to revoke it.",
      "pos": [
        16504,
        16608
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Or you can specify one or more of the access policy parameters within the stored access policy, and the others on the URL.",
      "pos": [
        16609,
        16731
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Finally, you can specify all of the parameters on the URL.",
      "pos": [
        16732,
        16790
      ]
